                                                                                                                                 2                                                                                        NATION BRIEFS
                                      
	 New Delhi, April 1 (PTI): The Delhi state consumer commission has directed an insurance company to pay the medical expenses incurred by a patient within a year of taking a mediclaim policy even though the policy clause stated otherwise.           
	The clause says that money will not be reimbursed if the policy-holder suffers from any ailment within one year of buying the policy. The commission noted that the insurance company was guilty of not bringing the clause to the policyholders notice while issuing the policy.                  
	 Melbourne (PTI): Indian students enrolment in universities in Australias Victoria state has recorded a 40 per cent drop in the first two months of the academic year compared with the same period in 2009, The Age has reported. Even enrolments by Malaysian and Korean students have shown a decline.                  
	 Jammu (PTI): The ration cards of over 5,000 Kashmiri migrant families were found to be fake and have been cancelled, the Jammu and Kashmir Assembly was informed on Thursday. Of those affected, 19,338 people live in Delhi, 924 families in Haryana, 222 in Uttar Pradesh, 43 in Madhya Pradesh, 208 in Maharastra and one in Tamil Nadu.                  
	 Jammu (PTI): A village defence committee member repulsed a militant attack on his home in Rajouri on Thursday by firing back at them, police said. Raj Kumar refused to open the door and, when the rebels began firing, engaged them in a gunfight for about an hour. Kumar had survived a similar attack in 2006 that left five defence committee members dead.                  
	 Lucknow (PTI): Five people, including a couple, in Uttar Pradesh have been arrested for allegedly duping people on the pretext of providing them jobs, police said. They would charge money from people by telling them that they were franchisees of a Dubai company. About 600 people were duped in the past year.                  
	 Balrampur (PTI): A 200-year-old idol of the Buddha, estimated to be worth Rs 10 crore, has been recovered from an alleged Nepalese smuggler in Uttar Pradesh, police said.                                                                                                                                              
